entries.statement:
[Baseline cubic and quartic stochastic symbols]\label{prop:cubic-quartic-baseline}
Assume $\alpha>3/4$. The cubic resonant symbols
\begin{equation*}
\Gamma_1=V_2\circ\Psi_1,
\qquad
\Gamma_2=V_1\circ\Psi_2
\end{equation*}
admit canonical cutoff limits as stochastic distributions with baseline regularity
\begin{equation}\label{eq:gamma-baseline}
\Gamma_i\in C_T\mathcal{C}^{4\alpha-9/2-}.
\end{equation}
The nonzero-chaos part of $V_1V_2$ admits a canonical baseline lift in
\begin{equation}\label{eq:vv-nonzero-baseline}
(V_1V_2)^{\neq 0}\in C_T\mathcal{C}^{6\alpha-6-}.
\end{equation}
Moreover, the zero-chaos part of $V_1V_2$ is a deterministic scalar process; under the speed-separated double Volterra estimate its dyadic shell is $N^{6-7\alpha+}$, so it converges in $C_T$ for $\alpha>6/7$.

[Mixed random operators and no singular centering]\label{thm:operator-main}
Let
\begin{equation}\label{eq:ET-def-intro}
E_T:=C_TL^2\cap C_T^1H^{-\alpha-\varepsilon}.
\end{equation}
Fix $0<\theta<1$ and $s_2>0$ such that
\begin{equation}\label{eq:operator-cond-main}
s_2<4\alpha-3-\frac32\theta-\varepsilon,
\qquad
3-4\alpha+\theta(s_2+\varepsilon)<0.
\end{equation}
Then the strongly low--high pieces of the four mixed operators
\begin{equation*}
T^{1;2,2},\qquad T^{2;1,1},\qquad T^{1;1,2},\qquad T^{2;2,1}
\end{equation*}
converge almost surely as bounded operators
\begin{equation}\label{eq:operator-bound-main}
E_T\longrightarrow C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}.
\end{equation}
Cross-color blocks are centered by independence. Same-color blocks decompose into finite speed-separated deterministic Volterra multipliers plus centered pathwise fluctuations. No divergent random-operator counterterm is subtracted in the limiting equation.

[Completion outside the strong low--high region]\label{prop:mid-completion}
Let the full paraproduct-resonant operator be decomposed into the strongly low--high region $|q|\le N^\theta$, the intermediate low--high region $N^\theta\lesssim |q|\ll N$, finitely many low shells, and the nonresonant paraproduct geometries. If the input has positive regularity $U\in C_TH^{s_1}$ with $s_1>0$, then the intermediate region contributes the dyadic shell
\begin{equation}\label{eq:mid-shell-intro}
N^{s_2+3-4\alpha-\theta s_1+\varepsilon},
\end{equation}
and is therefore summable once \eqref{eq:operator-cond-main} holds. The remaining nonresonant and finite-shell pieces are bounded by standard paraproduct and finite-rank estimates.

[Conditional deterministic closure]\label{thm:conditional-closure-intro}
Assume the fractional periodic Klein--Gordon Strichartz package of Assumption \ref{ass:strichartz}. Assume that the enhanced stochastic data satisfy Theorem \ref{thm:baseline-lift}, Proposition \ref{prop:cubic-quartic-baseline}, Theorem \ref{thm:operator-main}, and Proposition \ref{prop:mid-completion}. Assume in addition that the pure stochastic forcing is available in the source norm
\begin{equation}\label{eq:source-hyp-intro}
F^V:=\Psi_1V_2+\Psi_2V_1+V_1V_2\in C_TH^{s_2-\alpha},
\end{equation}
and that the parameters $(\alpha,s_1,s_2,\theta)$ satisfy the closure conditions listed in Definition \ref{def:admissible}. Then the paracontrolled system for the remainder variables $(X_1,X_2,Y_1,Y_2)$ is locally well posed in
\begin{equation*}
(X_T^{s_1})^2\times (Y_T^{s_2})^2.
\end{equation*}
The solution map is locally Lipschitz in the enhanced-data norms.

[Sharpness of the same-color shell]\label{prop:sharpness}
There exist a fixed low output frequency $q$, a conic sector of the resonant shell, and a smooth time profile $w(q,t)$ supported only at that frequency such that the leading same-color deterministic contraction on the dyadic shell $|\ell|\sim N$ satisfies
\begin{equation}\label{eq:sharpness}
\|D_N^{i;j}w\|_{C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}}\gtrsim N^{3-4\alpha}
\end{equation}
up to strictly lower-order terms. Consequently $\alpha=3/4$ is logarithmically critical for the deterministic contraction channel.

entries.proof:
[Proof sketch]
Choose $q$ fixed and choose a conic sector on which the resonant cutoff is nonzero and the sign of $\omega_i(q+\ell)-\omega_j(\ell)$ is fixed. A boundary term obtained after one Volterra integration by parts has the form
\begin{equation*}
\widehat w(q,t)
\sum_{|\ell|\sim N}
\frac{a_N(q,\ell,t)}{\omega_i(q+\ell)\,\omega_j(\ell)^2\,(\omega_i(q+\ell)-\omega_j(\ell))},
\end{equation*}
where $a_N$ is smooth and bounded away from zero on the chosen sector. Since each denominator contributes $N^{\alpha}$ and the sector contains $\gtrsim N^3$ lattice points, the shell size is exactly $N^{3-4\alpha}$.

entries.statement:
[Centered covariance bound]\label{lem:centered-cov}
On the strong low--high support, for all $0\le s\le t\le T$,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:centered-cov}
\mathbb{E}|B_N^{i;j,k}(n,q;t,s)|^2\lesssim_T N^{3-6\alpha}.
\end{equation}
Moreover, for every $0<\eta\le 1/2$,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:centered-inc}
\mathbb{E}|B_N^{i;j,k}(n,q;t,s)-B_N^{i;j,k}(n,q;t',s)|^2
\lesssim_T |t-t'|^{2\eta}N^{3-6\alpha+2\eta\alpha}.
\end{equation}

[Pathwise centered fluctuations]\label{thm:pathwise-fluct}
Assume
\begin{equation}\label{eq:a-neg}
a:=6-8\alpha+2s_2+3\theta<0.
\end{equation}
Then the centered dyadic fluctuation series
\begin{equation}\label{eq:fluct-series}
B^{i;j,k}:=\sum_{N\text{ dyadic}}B_N^{i;j,k}
\end{equation}
converges almost surely in
\begin{equation}\label{eq:fluct-op-space}
\mathcal L\bigl(E_T,C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}\bigr).
\end{equation}
More precisely, for every sufficiently small $\kappa>0$ there is an almost surely finite random constant $C_\omega$ such that
\begin{equation}\label{eq:fluct-dyadic-bound}
\|B_N^{i;j,k}\|_{E_T\to C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}}
\le C_\omega N^{a/2+\kappa}
\end{equation}
for all dyadic $N$.

entries.proof:
[Proof]
Lemma \ref{lem:centered-cov} gives
\begin{equation}\label{eq:HN-moment}
\mathbb{E}\|B_N(t)\|_{\mathfrak H_N}^2
\lesssim_T N^{3-6\alpha}\cdot N^3\cdot N^{3\theta}\cdot N^{2(s_2-\alpha)}
=N^a.
\end{equation}
The same computation with \eqref{eq:centered-inc} yields
\begin{equation}\label{eq:HN-inc}
\mathbb{E}\|B_N(t)-B_N(t')\|_{\mathfrak H_N}^2
\lesssim_T |t-t'|^{2\eta}N^{a+2\eta\alpha}.
\end{equation}
Since $B_N(t)$ is a Hilbert-valued finite Wiener chaos, Hilbert-valued hypercontractivity upgrades these $L^2(\Omega)$ bounds to all finite $L^p(\Omega)$ norms. A fractional Sobolev embedding in time, together with Kolmogorov continuity, yields a bound for $\sup_t\|B_N(t)\|_{\mathfrak H_N}$ in $L^p(\Omega)$ of size $N^{a/2+\eta\alpha+}$.

Choosing $\eta>0$ and $\kappa>0$ so that $a/2+\eta\alpha+\kappa<0$, Markov's inequality and Borel--Cantelli imply the almost sure dyadic estimate \eqref{eq:fluct-dyadic-bound}. Summation over $N$ then gives the operator convergence in \eqref{eq:fluct-op-space} by \eqref{eq:HS-step}.

entries.statement:
[Speed gap]\label{lem:speed-gap}
Fix $0<\theta<1$ and $i\neq j$. There exist $N_0$ and $c_*>0$ such that whenever $N\ge N_0$, $|\ell|\sim N$, and $|q|\le N^\theta$,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:speed-gap-minus}
|\omega_i(q+\ell)-\omega_j(\ell)|\ge c_*N^\alpha,
\end{equation}
and also
\begin{equation}\label{eq:speed-gap-plus}
\omega_i(q+\ell)+\omega_j(\ell)\ge c_*N^\alpha.
\end{equation}

entries.proof:
Using \eqref{eq:omega-intro},
\begin{equation*}
\omega_i(q+\ell)-\omega_j(\ell)
=(c_i-c_j)|\ell|^\alpha+O(N^{\alpha-1}|q|)+O(N^{-\alpha}).
\end{equation*}
Since $|q|\le N^\theta$ with $\theta<1$, the error is $o(N^\alpha)$, and the main term survives because $c_i\neq c_j$. The plus branch is immediate from positivity.

entries.statement:
[Volterra oscillation estimate]\label{lem:volterra}
Let $a\in C^1([0,T])$ and let $|\Phi|\gtrsim N^\alpha$. Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:volterra-est}
\sup_{0\le t\le T}
\Bigl|\int_0^t a(s)e^{\mathrm{i}(t-s)\Phi}\,ds\Bigr|
\lesssim N^{-\alpha}\bigl(\|a\|_{L^\infty_T}+\|\partial_t a\|_{L^\infty_T}\bigr).
\end{equation}
The same bound holds with $\sin((t-s)\Phi)$ or $\cos((t-s)\Phi)$ in place of the exponential.

[Same-color deterministic contraction]\label{prop:det-contraction}
Let $i\neq j$. Define
\begin{equation}\label{eq:DN-operator}
(\mathcal D_N^{i;j}w)_q(t)=\int_0^t D_N^{i;j}(q;t,s)\widehat w(q,s)\,ds.
\end{equation}
Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:DN-bound}
\|\mathcal D_N^{i;j}w\|_{C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}}
\lesssim_T
\Bigl(N^{3-4\alpha}+N^{3-4\alpha+\theta(s_2+\varepsilon)}\Bigr)
\bigl(\|w\|_{C_TL^2}+\|\partial_t w\|_{C_TH^{-\alpha-\varepsilon}}\bigr).
\end{equation}
Consequently $\sum_N\mathcal D_N^{i;j}$ converges in $\mathcal L(E_T,C_TH^{s_2-\alpha})$ whenever the second condition in \eqref{eq:operator-cond-main} holds.

[No singular centering for mixed random operators]\label{thm:no-singular-centering}
Assume \eqref{eq:operator-cond-main}. Then each strongly low--high mixed random operator has a cutoff limit as a pathwise bounded operator
\begin{equation*}
E_T\to C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}.
\end{equation*}
Cross-color blocks are automatically centered by independence. Same-color blocks decompose as
\begin{equation*}
T^{i;j,j}=\mathcal D^{i;j}+\mathcal B^{i;j,j},
\end{equation*}
where $\mathcal D^{i;j}$ is a finite speed-separated deterministic Volterra multiplier and $\mathcal B^{i;j,j}$ is a centered pathwise random operator. No divergent random-operator counterterm is subtracted.

[Fractional periodic Klein--Gordon Strichartz package]\label{ass:strichartz}
For $0<T\le 1$ and $i=1,2$, the Duhamel operator $I_i$ satisfies the inhomogeneous estimates required for the norms
\begin{equation}\label{eq:X-space}
\|X\|_{X_T^{s_1}}
:=\|X\|_{C_TH^{s_1}}+\|\partial_tX\|_{C_TH^{s_1-\alpha}}+\|X\|_{L_T^8W^{s_1-\alpha/4,8/3}},
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}\label{eq:Y-space}
\|Y\|_{Y_T^{s_2}}
:=\|Y\|_{C_TH^{s_2}}+\|\partial_tY\|_{C_TH^{s_2-\alpha}}+\|Y\|_{L_T^4W^{s_2-\alpha/2,4}},
\end{equation}
with a positive local-time factor $T^\delta$ in the nonlinear estimates used below.

[Safe bookkeeping range]\label{cor:safe-range}
Assume the baseline value $\rho_V=3\alpha-3-$ and no improvement beyond the naive low--high estimate for the $X$-equation. If
\begin{equation*}
\alpha>\frac{12}{13},
\end{equation*}
then one can choose $0<s_1<s_2$ and $0<\theta<1$ satisfying Definition \ref{def:admissible}. Thus, once a source-level or primitive-level cubic forcing enhancement is available, the conservative deterministic closure is consistent in this range.
